---
alwaysApply: true
---

You are developing an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

You must follow strict code standards across all apps in the monorepo.
These standards apply to backend (NestJS), frontend (Next.js), and shared package equally.

==============================
NAMING CONVENTIONS
==============================

Variables and functions: camelCase
  getUserById, fairName, isAuthenticated

Classes, types, interfaces, enums: PascalCase
  FairService, CustomerDto, ConversionRate, JwtAuthGuard

Environment variables: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
  DATABASE_URL, JWT_ACCESS_SECRET, CORS_ORIGIN

File names: kebab-case
  fair.service.ts, customer.controller.ts, create-fair.schema.ts

Folder names: lowercase
  modules/, components/, stores/, hooks/

NestJS specific:
  Modules: *.module.ts
  Controllers: *.controller.ts
  Services: *.service.ts
  Guards: *.guard.ts
  DTOs: *.dto.ts
  Pipes: *.pipe.ts

React components: PascalCase file names matching component name
  FairCard.tsx, CustomerForm.tsx, Modal.tsx

React hooks: use prefix, camelCase file names
  useFairs.ts, useAuth.ts, useDebounce.ts

==============================
BACKEND STRUCTURE (NestJS)
==============================

Modular feature-based structure is mandatory:

apps/api/src/
├── modules/
│   ├── auth/
│   │   ├── auth.module.ts
│   │   ├── auth.controller.ts
│   │   ├── auth.service.ts
│   │   ├── strategies/          — Passport strategies
│   │   ├── guards/              — AuthGuard, RolesGuard
│   │   └── dto/                 — login.dto.ts, register.dto.ts
│   ├── user/
│   ├── fair/
│   └── customer/
├── common/
│   ├── filters/                 — global exception filter
│   ├── interceptors/            — response transform, logging
│   ├── pipes/                   — Zod validation pipe
│   └── decorators/              — custom decorators (@Roles, @CurrentUser)
├── prisma/
│   └── prisma.service.ts        — PrismaClient wrapper
└── main.ts

Each module MUST contain: module, controller, service.
Each module MAY contain: dto/, guards/, strategies/ as needed.
Do not create large monolithic files. Keep files small and focused.

==============================
FRONTEND STRUCTURE (Next.js)
==============================

apps/web/src/
├── app/                         — pages, layouts (App Router)
│   ├── (auth)/                  — auth group (login page)
│   ├── (dashboard)/             — protected pages
│   └── layout.tsx               — root layout with providers
├── components/
│   ├── ui/                      — base UI components (shadcn/ui based)
│   ├── fair/                    — FairCard, FairForm, FairDetail
│   ├── customer/                — CustomerCard, CustomerForm
│   └── layout/                  — TopBar, ContentWrapper
├── lib/
│   ├── api.ts                   — Axios instance with interceptors
│   ├── query-keys.ts            — TanStack Query key factory
│   └── utils.ts                 — frontend-specific helpers
├── stores/
│   └── auth-store.ts            — Zustand auth store
├── hooks/
│   ├── use-fairs.ts             — TanStack Query hooks for fairs
│   └── use-customers.ts         — TanStack Query hooks for customers
└── types/                       — frontend-only types (extend @crm/shared)

==============================
CODE QUALITY
==============================

- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) — extract shared logic immediately.
- Keep functions under 40 lines when possible.
- Keep React components under 150 lines — extract sub-components.
- Use clear and descriptive naming — avoid abbreviations.
- Avoid magic numbers and hardcoded strings — use constants from @crm/shared.
- Prefer early returns over deeply nested conditionals.
- One export per file for modules, services, and components.

==============================
ASYNC / AWAIT
==============================

- Always use async/await — never use raw .then() chains.
- Always handle errors with try/catch in services.
- Controllers delegate error handling to NestJS exception filters.
- Frontend API calls handle errors via TanStack Query onError or Axios interceptors.

==============================
ERROR HANDLING
==============================

Backend:
- Use NestJS built-in exceptions (NotFoundException, BadRequestException, etc.).
- Global exception filter catches unhandled errors and returns standardized format.
- Service layer throws typed exceptions — controller never catches manually.
- Never expose raw Prisma errors to the client.

Frontend:
- TanStack Query handles API errors via onError callbacks.
- Display user-friendly error messages using toast/notification system.
- Network errors show retry option.
- Validation errors highlight specific form fields.

==============================
TYPE SAFETY
==============================

- TypeScript strict mode is mandatory in all apps and packages.
- Always define types and interfaces — never use "any".
- Import shared types from @crm/shared — never redefine locally.
- Use Zod infer for deriving TypeScript types from validation schemas:
  type CreateFairInput = z.infer<typeof createFairSchema>
- Prisma generated types are used in backend service layer.
- API response types are defined in @crm/shared for frontend consumption.

==============================
IMPORTS
==============================

- Use absolute imports with path aliases:
  Backend: @modules/, @common/, @prisma/
  Frontend: @/components/, @/lib/, @/stores/, @/hooks/
  Shared: @crm/shared
- Group imports in this order:
  1. External packages (nest, react, zod, etc.)
  2. Internal aliases (@modules/, @/components/, @crm/shared)
  3. Relative imports (./dto, ./utils)
- Never use deep relative paths (../../..).

==============================
REACT & COMPONENT RULES
==============================

- Use functional components exclusively — no class components.
- Use React Hook Form for all forms — no manual form state.
- Co-locate Zod schemas with forms via @crm/shared.
- Memoize expensive computations with useMemo.
- Memoize callbacks passed to children with useCallback.
- Extract custom hooks for reusable data-fetching logic.
- Prefer composition over prop drilling — use context or Zustand when needed.

==============================
CSS & STYLING
==============================

- Use TailwindCSS utility classes for all styling.
- Use design system tokens defined in tailwind.config — never hardcode hex colors.
- Follow the color naming: bg, surface, card, border, accent, gold, muted, green, text.
- Use shadcn/ui components as base — extend, don't rewrite.
- Responsive design: use TailwindCSS breakpoints, prefer mobile-first.
- Animations: use CSS transitions (0.15s–0.2s) — avoid heavy JS animations.

==============================
COMMENTS
==============================

- Write meaningful comments only for non-obvious business logic.
- Do not over-comment obvious code.
- Use JSDoc for public service methods and complex utility functions.
- Explain WHY, not WHAT — code should be self-documenting for the what.
- Never leave TODO comments without a linked feature number.

==============================
IMPORTANT
==============================

- Never sacrifice code clarity for brevity.
- Always prioritize maintainability and scalability.
- When in doubt, follow the established patterns in existing modules.
